The only reason that I am posting a review of this game is because I wanted to clarify something that many previous reviewers have brought up. A lot of the reviews are complaining about how the game lags even with *insert super-powered phone processor name*, but that makes sense because this game's graphics are actually quite polished, and smoother images mean more pixels to load per frame. With a 2.5Ghz processor, you can process 2.5 billion cycles of data delivery and receipt every second, which sounds like a lot, but your 2.5Ghz super-processor doesn't render your graphics, that's what your video card is for, and in the world of cellphones, processing speed is cheaper in the CPU than the GPU, so lower priced phones put money into monster CPUs, but their video adapters can't keep up, and the result, especially in a game with smooth textures and frequent/rapid particle effects, is lag. You can get around this by going into your main settings and making sure that anything that has to do with battery savings is turned off, you have no other applications running, and if possible adjusting your graphics quality settings to the least detailed possible. This will free up your CPU's full processing ability, as well as make it easier for your GPU to render and possibly even cache those brutal particle effects. On a side note, I'm playing this on a Galaxy note 4, which is no where near as powerful in any way as the super-phones other reviewers have mentioned using, but I haven't had any lag or anything else. I just check my settings before starting the game, and everything works fine. I hope this review helps clarify some information. It's a simple but fun game, and I think it's worth more time than most of these reviews make it out to be.
